to the center as possible,

00:42:18.850 --> 00:42:21.130
you need to be entrepreneurial.

00:42:21.130 --> 00:42:22.750
And being
entrepreneurial doesn't

00:42:22.750 --> 00:42:24.970
mean being a tiny startup.

00:42:24.970 --> 00:42:28.480
You can be entrepreneurial
in a large organization.

00:42:28.480 --> 00:42:30.220
But being entrepreneurial
means that you

00:42:30.220 --> 00:42:35.590
need to be ready to evolve
at the pace of the multitude

00:42:35.590 --> 00:42:38.410
of networked individuals,
because, again, they're

00:42:38.410 --> 00:42:43.450
constantly demanding better
products at a cheaper price.

00:42:43.450 --> 00:42:45.340
They want to be served faster.

00:42:45.340 --> 00:42:51.260
They want new features,
new bundles, new services,

00:42:51.260 --> 00:42:52.100
et cetera.

00:42:52.100 --> 00:42:55.180
And you can only afford
being close to them

00:42:55.180 --> 00:42:57.750
if you you're able
to deliver that.

00:42:57.750 --> 00:43:00.580
And so that's why the
economy is becoming

00:43:00.580 --> 00:43:02.090
more and more entrepreneurial.

00:43:02.090 --> 00:43:04.870
It's because most
large organizations

00:43:04.870 --> 00:43:11.020
have a hard time serving
that multitude of demanding

00:43:11.020 --> 00:43:13.000
networked individuals.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:16.250
And so I have a
few cases in mind.

00:43:16.250 --> 00:43:21.070
I think a company like Amazon
has done a great job scaling

00:43:21.070 --> 00:43:23.290
up, while retaining
that capacity

00:43:23.290 --> 00:43:26.650
to constantly innovate and to
question its business model

00:43:26.650 --> 00:43:29.170
and to reinvent
itself, or expand

00:43:29.170 --> 00:43:34.900
on to new markets
on a constant basis.

00:43:34.900 --> 00:43:39.670
But the danger that large
organizations are exposed to

00:43:39.670 --> 00:43:45.700
is that as they become larger,
they embark a lot of rigidity

00:43:45.700 --> 00:43:52.390
and a lot of processes,
and they become complacent,

00:43:52.390 --> 00:43:55.690
and they have difficulties to
change to expand, to explore

00:43:55.690 --> 00:44:00.920
new territories, to learn
from their failures and so on.

00:44:00.920 --> 00:44:03.520
And so I think that's the
challenge that every large tech

00:44:03.520 --> 00:44:05.920
company has to tackle.

00:44:05.920 --> 00:44:08.830
Do they want to remain
close to the center?

00:44:08.830 --> 00:44:11.620
And for that, they need to
be more entrepreneurial.

00:44:11.620 --> 00:44:14.050
Or if they're not
entrepreneurial enough,

00:44:14.050 --> 00:44:16.270
they'll have the stability
and the security that

00:44:16.270 --> 00:44:19.930
comes with many assets,
a strong balance sheet

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:23.590
and employing many
people, but they also

00:44:23.590 --> 00:44:27.580
have the rigidity
that makes them

00:44:27.580 --> 00:44:32.580
less relevant to the networked
individuals at the center.

00:44:32.580 --> 00:44:36.930
And so I think that it's a good
thing that tech companies are

00:44:36.930 --> 00:44:40.140
moving toward the center,
because at the center,

00:44:40.140 --> 00:44:45.970
you basically submit to what
networked individuals want.

00:44:45.970 --> 00:44:50.170
And so it's an entirely
different field of discussion,

00:44:50.170 --> 00:44:52.800
like antitrust and
breaking up tech companies

00:44:52.800 --> 00:44:54.350
and stuff like that.

00:44:54.350 --> 00:44:57.600
But I think that the
networked individuals are now

00:44:57.600 --> 00:45:03.570
strong enough to make sure that
the companies that sell them

00:45:03.570 --> 00:45:05.700
act in their best interests.

00:45:05.700 --> 00:45:09.000
And what is lacking is
only the institutions

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:13.000
to make it possible to provide
those people with stability,

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.310
security, and the
capacity to exit.

00:45:15.310 --> 00:45:17.340
So you mentioned
those Uber drivers.

00:45:17.340 --> 00:45:19.020
They're very close
to the center.

00:45:19.020 --> 00:45:21.590
They're serving demanding
networked individuals.

00:45:21.590 --> 00:45:24.600
They're also networked
themselves, as drivers,

00:45:24.600 --> 00:45:26.760
as a company.

00:45:26.760 --> 00:45:31.620
But they don't have the
safety net that provides them

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:34.800
with the stability and the
security and the support

00:45:34.800 --> 00:45:38.250
that they need to make the
most of their current situation

00:45:38.250 --> 00:45:42.330
and maybe rebound to
more rewarding positions

00:45:42.330 --> 00:45:43.420
in the economy.

00:45:43.420 --> 00:45:45.990
So this is why we need to
invent this new safety net.

00:45:45.990 --> 00:45:51.960
It's simply to acknowledge
that the workforce has moved

00:45:51.960 --> 00:45:55.710
from factories to urban
proximity services

00:45:55.710 --> 00:45:59.130
and to provide those--

00:45:59.130 --> 00:46:01.260
what's now the majority
of the workforce, that

00:46:01.260 --> 00:46:04.740
is proximity service
workers, with the support

00:46:04.740 --> 00:46:07.600
they need to become
the new middle class.

00:46:07.600 --> 00:46:10.406
This is really
what's at stake here.

00:46:10.406 --> 00:46:12.450
AUDIENCE: I had a question
regarding your book.

00:46:12.450 --> 00:46:14.310
You began your book
with a personal anecdote

00:46:14.310 --> 00:46:16.477
about when you were summoned
to court for an alleged

00:46:16.477 --> 00:46:19.080
defamation against a leading
figure in the French taxi

00:46:19.080 --> 00:46:20.130
industry.

00:46:20.130 --> 00:46:21.825
Do instances like
this make you feel

00:46:21.825 --> 00:46:23.700
that corporations are,
in fact, trying to put

00:46:23.700 --> 00:46:27.185
a stop on those innovations?

00:46:27.185 --> 00:46:28.310
NICOLAS COLIN: So I think--

00:46:28.310 --> 00:46:33.050
well, yes, so there's
this anecdote,

00:46:33.050 --> 00:46:35.090
which dates back
like six years ago,

00:46:35.090 --> 00:46:37.720
when we founded
our firm in Paris.

00:46:37.720 --> 00:46:41.120
At exactly the same
time, I wrote a blog post

00:46:41.120 --> 00:46:45.830
that it put online criticizing
the CEO of the largest taxi

00:46:45.830 --> 00:46:49.790
company in Paris because
he was introducing himself

00:46:49.790 --> 00:46:52.790
in videos and interviews as--

00:46:52.790 --> 00:46:55.070
well, the king of
innovation, if you will,

00:46:55.070 --> 00:47:00.620
explaining how his taxi
company was innovating so much.

00:47:00.620 --> 00:47:05.070
And what I wrote was
that in these interviews,

00:47:05.070 --> 00:47:07.580
there was a deep
misunderstanding

00:47:07.580 --> 00:47:09.630
of what innovation was about.

00:47:09.630 --> 00:47:12.700
And if we relied on such
people to innovate, well,

00:47:12.700 --> 00:47:16.580
we as a country, France
and Europe, in general,

00:47:16.580 --> 00:47:20.410
will keep on lagging
behind the US and China.

00:47:20.410 --> 00:47:23.690
And so he didn't like my blog
post and sued me in court,

00:47:23.690 --> 00:47:25.220
and I was cleared later.

00:47:25.220 --> 00:47:29.420
So that ended up OK.

00:47:29.420 --> 00:47:34.370
But I introduced the
book with this anecdote

00:47:34.370 --> 00:47:39.110
to try and share with
an American audience

00:47:39.110 --> 00:47:42.110
what it's like to work
in tech in Europe.

00:47:42.110 --> 00:47:47.600
Again, we don't have large tech
companies, like you have here.

00:47:47.600 --> 00:47:50.300
But we have many startups
and many entrepreneurs

00:47:50.300 --> 00:47:54.270
that realize that you can use
technology in an innovative way

00:47:54.270 --> 00:47:58.590
and tackle problems that were
previously without a solution.

00:47:58.590 --> 00:48:00.260
The problem is that
those entrepreneurs

00:48:00.260 --> 00:48:05.030
have to battle against
powerful incumbents that

00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:11.150
have everything to lose
with the economy changing.

00:48:11.150 --> 00:48:13.820
They don't want those startups
entering their markets.

00:48:13.820 --> 00:48:17.390
They don't want the value chain
to be redesigned according

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:19.640
to the needs of
networked individuals,

00:48:19.640 --> 00:48:23.390
and they want regulations to
preserve the status quo as

00:48:23.390 --> 00:48:25.730
opposed to lifting everyone up.

00:48:25.730 --> 00:48:29.210
And so in Europe, we have to--

00:48:29.210 --> 00:48:30.900
so you have that in the US.

00:48:30.900 --> 00:48:32.160
But it's rather new.

00:48:32.160 --> 00:48:34.820
It's called the backlash
against technology.

00:48:34.820 --> 00:48:40.190
And tech companies have been
adapting the past two years

00:48:40.190 --> 00:48:43.940
to that new context in
which they encounter

00:48:43.940 --> 00:48:47.030
hostility from
basically everyone

00:48:47.030 --> 00:48:50.150
from every part of the
political spectrum and so on.

00:48:50.150 --> 00:48:53.240
This is new in the US,
but in Europe, it's

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:54.540
always been like that.

00:48:54.540 --> 00:48:58.400
And so we who work
in tech in Europe,

00:48:58.400 --> 00:49:02.750
we're used to battling
against a hostile environment

00:49:02.750 --> 00:49:05.360
and to force
innovation, not only

00:49:05.360 --> 00:49:09.950
by building great
startups that eventually

00:49:09.950 --> 00:49:17.870
become great companies, but also
by sharing that narrative that

00:49:17.870 --> 00:49:20.720
basically conveys the
message that startups are not

00:49:20.720 --> 00:49:23.030
only about disruption
and destruction

00:49:23.030 --> 00:49:26.020
and invading your
privacy and destroy jobs.

00:49:26.020 --> 00:49:29.540
No, startups are the vanguard
of a new world, which

00:49:29.540 --> 00:49:33.440
will reward all of us
with sustainability

00:49:33.440 --> 00:49:37.730
and inclusiveness if we run
the two parts of the race.

00:49:37.730 --> 00:49:41.540
The first part, again, that
is building great companies,

00:49:41.540 --> 00:49:42.980
thriving companies.

00:49:42.980 --> 00:49:47.480
And the part is parties
inventing new institutions.

00:49:47.480 --> 00:49:50.070
AUDIENCE: Quick question
that I am constantly

00:49:50.070 --> 00:49:53.840
struggling is how you see the
paradox of having institutions

00:49:53.840 --> 00:49:57.860
that need to regulate the tech
industry that is moving so

00:49:57.860 --> 00:50:02.000
fast, and you have institutions
that take a long time

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.130
to make a decision?

00:50:04.130 --> 00:50:05.630
NICOLAS COLIN: It's
a good question,

00:50:05.630 --> 00:50:13.200
because one of the features
of the '40s economy

00:50:13.200 --> 00:50:15.660
was that it was a
very stable economy.

00:50:15.660 --> 00:50:19.020
The only thing that was
unstable was consumer demand.

00:50:19.020 --> 00:50:22.680
And the Great Safety
Net 1.0 was precisely

00:50:22.680 --> 00:50:26.400
designed to provide
stability on consumer markets

00:50:26.400 --> 00:50:28.500
to make it possible
for industrialists

00:50:28.500 --> 00:50:32.640
to invest, to plan ahead and
to invest over the long term,

00:50:32.640 --> 00:50:35.430
because they could,
thanks to the safety net,

00:50:35.430 --> 00:50:37.020
and the stability
and the security

00:50:37.020 --> 00:50:40.260
that it provided
to everyone, well,

00:50:40.260 --> 00:50:43.560
they could count on sustained
consumer demand over the course

00:50:43.560 --> 00:50:46.600
of years or decades.

00:50:46.600 --> 00:50:54.190
Today-- so we had stability on
the production side or supply

00:50:54.190 --> 00:50:57.400
side and instability
on the demand side.

00:50:57.400 --> 00:51:00.610
And the economy
became more stable

00:51:00.610 --> 00:51:03.910
because we corrected the
instability on the demand side

00:51:03.910 --> 00:51:08.260
by building new institutions.

00:51:08.260 --> 00:51:11.410
Today, the problem we have
is that there's instability

00:51:11.410 --> 00:51:14.500
everywhere, like the
supply side is unstable,

00:51:14.500 --> 00:51:17.960
because of increasing returns
to scale and network effects.

00:51:17.960 --> 00:51:19.600
The demand side
is still unstable,

00:51:19.600 --> 00:51:22.580
because people are
changing constantly

00:51:22.580 --> 00:51:24.910
and want new products
and new services

00:51:24.910 --> 00:51:27.010
and have new ideas constantly.

00:51:27.010 --> 00:51:29.260
So how do you provide
stability in such an economy,

00:51:29.260 --> 00:51:32.140
and how do you design
stable institutions

00:51:32.140 --> 00:51:36.380
that pass the test of time?

00:51:36.380 --> 00:51:37.510
I don't know actually.

00:51:37.510 --> 00:51:40.990
This is why we really
need to run that race

00:51:40.990 --> 00:51:44.280
and to enter the
discovery process.

00:51:44.280 --> 00:51:48.410
And that goes through trials
and errors and errors and errors

00:51:48.410 --> 00:51:51.420
before we finally
discover what works.

00:51:51.420 --> 00:51:55.400
But what I am convinced
of is that you

00:51:55.400 --> 00:52:00.380
can design institutions
for an unstable economy

00:52:00.380 --> 00:52:03.930
with the goal of
providing stability.

00:52:03.930 --> 00:52:12.330
So there's this concept by
Nassim Taleb called antifragile

00:52:12.330 --> 00:52:16.380
And so antifragile
is not robust.

00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:20.450
It's how do you survive in
a world that's constantly

00:52:20.450 --> 00:52:25.070
changing in which you have to
reinvent yourself and rebound

00:52:25.070 --> 00:52:28.760
and get back on your
feet throughout many ups

00:52:28.760 --> 00:52:32.110
and downs and booms and busts.

00:52:32.110 --> 00:52:34.070
And so it's an
interesting concept,

00:52:34.070 --> 00:52:36.800
because this is really
what's at stake here.

00:52:36.800 --> 00:52:39.230
We need to design
institutions that

00:52:39.230 --> 00:52:43.470
will provide the
stability that's

00:52:43.470 --> 00:52:47.650
missing in an economy dominated
by computing and networks.

00:52:47.650 --> 00:52:52.030
And maybe those institutions--
so that one part of the book

00:52:52.030 --> 00:52:54.250
discusses the
relevance of the state.

00:52:54.250 --> 00:52:57.820
Like, the last time, stability
was provided by the state,

00:52:57.820 --> 00:53:03.190
because the state was the
largest top down organizations

00:53:03.190 --> 00:53:05.560
there was in a given country.

00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:11.890
And so how could you
regulate the '40s economy

00:53:11.890 --> 00:53:15.070
that was dominated by large
top down organizations

00:53:15.070 --> 00:53:18.280
by inviting the largest
of those organizations

00:53:18.280 --> 00:53:23.920
to enact the rules and to
watch over the various players.

00:53:23.920 --> 00:53:30.520
Today, I'm not certain the
state is the player that's

00:53:30.520 --> 00:53:32.900
able to deliver that.

00:53:32.900 --> 00:53:35.880
Maybe the new
institutions will be

00:53:35.880 --> 00:53:41.700
designed by a complex nexus
of different organizations,

00:53:41.700 --> 00:53:45.900
acting like platforms, so
individuals themselves,

00:53:45.900 --> 00:53:51.150
the new unions, tech
companies, and governments

00:53:51.150 --> 00:53:58.320
all together will design
that process of upgrading

00:53:58.320 --> 00:54:01.970
institutions to account
for the fast pace of change

00:54:01.970 --> 00:54:04.720
in the economy.

00:54:04.720 --> 00:54:06.270
It's not a top down approach.

00:54:06.270 --> 00:54:08.850
In an economy dominated
by networked individuals,

00:54:08.850 --> 00:54:12.570
you can't regulate that economy
with a top down approach.

00:54:12.570 --> 00:54:16.380
And that's very much
the problem we have

00:54:16.380 --> 00:54:18.450
on both sides of the Atlantic.

00:54:18.450 --> 00:54:21.270
So in Europe, we
don't really get that.

00:54:21.270 --> 00:54:26.230
So we're trying to do what
we did so well the last time.

00:54:26.230 --> 00:54:30.120
That is, have the state
come up with regulations

00:54:30.120 --> 00:54:34.230
imposed from the top down,
and it will provide balance.

00:54:34.230 --> 00:54:36.930
Here in the US, you have
a better understanding

00:54:36.930 --> 00:54:39.060
of what's going on,
but the government

00:54:39.060 --> 00:54:42.990
is still far removed
from the tech industry

00:54:42.990 --> 00:54:46.920
and doesn't interact
enough with that industry

00:54:46.920 --> 00:54:52.380
to realize that maybe the top
down approaches at enacting

00:54:52.380 --> 00:54:55.470
regulations don't work anymore.

00:54:55.470 --> 00:54:57.840
So there's a lot of work to do.

00:54:57.840 --> 00:55:01.410
And again, keep in mind
that that kind of work

00:55:01.410 --> 00:55:03.090
is not only done
here in the West.

00:55:03.090 --> 00:55:06.990
It's also done in China,
in Southeast Asia,

00:55:06.990 --> 00:55:10.600
and maybe they'll come up
with new designs before we do,

00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:14.070
and they'll invent their own
version of the safety net,

00:55:14.070 --> 00:55:21.000
and they'll race ahead
towards economic development

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:23.560
while we in the West
will be lagging behind.

00:55:23.560 --> 00:55:26.220
So that's very much
what's at stake here.

00:55:26.220 --> 00:55:28.980
SPEAKER 1: All right, with that,
